1. Background

We have identified a region that is a very good candidate for harbouring the sex-determination locus on LG6.

To further validate our findings, let's now conduct an association test for each SNP from the adult sexed individuals dataset. We will then plot the statistical significance of association for each SNP against their linkage map position to see whether we detect the same region as we did using the sex-linked markers.

We will use the package SNPassoc.

4. Format

First of all, we will format the data to the format required by SNPassoc, which is the ped format.

my.dfs <- lapply(my.dfs, function(x){
  y <- x %>%
    #remove replicate information at the end of sampleID
    mutate(sampleID = gsub("_a|_b","",sampleID)) %>%
    #add column of sex, info stored in sampleID
    mutate(sex =  substr(sampleID, nchar(sampleID), nchar(sampleID))) %>%
    #select only relevant columns
    select(sampleID, Species, sex, Pop, everything())
  
  return(y)
})

Now we need to replace the genotypes from 0, 1, 2 to nucleotides (i.e., AA, AC, CC)

my.dfs <- lapply(my.dfs, function(x){
  y <- x %>%
    mutate(across(everything(), as.character))
  
  y[y=="0"] <- "AA"
  y[y=="1"] <- "AC"
  y[y=="2"] <- "CC"
  y[y=="-1"] <- NA
  
  return(y)
})

Save resulting file

5 Association test

Now we can run the association test. To do so, we need to use the setupSNP function to create the object required by SNPassoc package. We will do so for all 15 population across the three lineages.

5.1 Litoria myola (LM)

Separate data into 5 populations just as we did for previous tests, based on PCoA results and knowledge of species

#All 2022 samples
P11 <- my.dfs$LM %>%
  filter(grepl("_CONX6",sampleID))

#2022 samples from the Western cluster only
P12 <- my.dfs$LM %>%
  filter(grepl("_CONX6",sampleID) &
           !grepl("LM_M_JC|LM_M_PL|LM_M_BB",sampleID))

#All 2001 samples
P13 <- my.dfs$LM %>%
  filter(!grepl("_CONX6",sampleID))

#2001 samples from the Eastern cluster only
P14 <- my.dfs$LM %>%
  filter(grepl("LM_M_JC",sampleID) &
           !grepl("_CONX6",sampleID))

#All samples from Litoria myola
P15 <- my.dfs$LM

Make a list with the 5 populations and loop through them with lapply to conduct the association test.

my.list <- list("P11"=P11,"P12"=P12,"P13"=P13,
             "P14"=P14,"P15"=P15)

lapply(my.list, function(x){
  t1 <- setupSNP(data=x, colSNPs=5:ncol(x),
                 sep="")
  
  t2 <- WGassociation(sex, data = t1,
                       model = "codominant",
                       quantitative = FALSE,
                       genotypingRate = 0.8)
  
  write_delim(as_tibble(t2,
                        rownames = "MarkerID"),
              file = paste0("../7_GWAS/7_2_",
                            names(x),
                            "_cod_0.8.txt"),
              delim = "\t")
})
rm(P11,P12,P13,P14,P15)

These qqplot plots sorted observed Pvalues on the y axis and expected Pvalues based on aw uniform distribution. If you look at the underlying function these are produced with (1:n)/(n+1) where n is the number of loci tested.

Let's plot the qqplot with Confidence intervals as well. To do so I use the gg_qqplot function from this blog. First I define the function.

gg_qqplot <- function(ps, ci = 0.95) {
  n  <- length(ps)
  df <- data.frame(
    observed = -log10(sort(ps)),
    expected = -log10(ppoints(n)),
    clower   = -log10(qbeta(p = (1 - ci) / 2, shape1 = 1:n, shape2 = n:1)),
    cupper   = -log10(qbeta(p = (1 + ci) / 2, shape1 = 1:n, shape2 = n:1))
  )
  log10Pe <- expression(paste("Expected -log"[10], plain((p-value))))
  log10Po <- expression(paste("Observed -log"[10], plain((p-value))))
  ggplot(df) +
    geom_ribbon(
      mapping = aes(x = expected, ymin = clower, ymax = cupper),
      alpha = 0.1
    ) +
    geom_point(aes(expected, observed), shape = 1, size = 2) +
    geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, alpha = 0.5) +
    # geom_line(aes(expected, cupper), linetype = 2, size = 0.5) +
    # geom_line(aes(expected, clower), linetype = 2, size = 0.5) +
    xlab(log10Pe) +
    ylab(log10Po)
}

Then I use it to produce the qqplot.

#plot
my.plots <- lapply(my.gwas, function(x){
  y <- gg_qqplot(x %>%
                  pull(codominant),
                ci = 0.95) +
  theme_bw(base_size = 12) +
  theme(
    axis.ticks = element_line(size=0.5),
    panel.grid = element_blank()
  )
  
  return(y)
})

Before correction there are between 0 and 10 markers per population significantly associated with sex at an alpha of 0.0001. For the LS lineage most of these (18/19) occur on chromosome 5. The remaining markers are found on Chr5 (Pop10), Chr3 (Pop12), Chr12 (Pop13), Chr1 (Pop14) and Chr1 and Chr8 (Pop15). These numbers are much larger (~200 < x < 2000) at an alpha value of 0.05. Given we are doing ~20,000 to ~30,000 tests we will need to adjust for multiple testing.

my.gwas <- lapply(my.gwas, function(x){
  holm <- p.adjust(x$codominant,
                method = "holm",
                n=length(x$codominant))
  
  fdr <- p.adjust(x$codominant,
                method = "fdr",
                n=length(x$codominant))
  
  bonferroni <- p.adjust(x$codominant,
                method = "bonferroni",
                n=length(x$codominant))
  
  BH <- p.adjust(x$codominant,
                method = "BH",
                n=length(x$codominant))
  
  BY <- p.adjust(x$codominant,
                method = "BY",
                n=length(x$codominant))
  
  hommel <- p.adjust(x$codominant,
                method = "hommel",
                n=length(x$codominant))
  
  hochberg <- p.adjust(x$codominant,
                method = "hochberg",
                n=length(x$codominant))
  
  z <- x %>% add_column("holm" = holm,
                        "fdr" = fdr,
                        "bonferroni" = bonferroni,
                        "BH" = BH,
                        "BY" = BY,
                        "Hommel" = hommel,
                        "Hochberg" = hochberg)
  
  return(z)
})

All six SNPs are on scaffold 5, from 3 different "loci" and we have two pairs that occur within 30 base pairs of each other.

Now, let's calculate the genomic inflation factor for population 3

my.chisq<- qchisq(1 - my.gwas$P3$codominant, 1)
median(my.chisq) / qchisq(0.5, 1)
## [1] 0.4535186
my.chisq<- qchisq(1 - my.gwas$P5$codominant, 1)
median(my.chisq) / qchisq(0.5, 1)
## [1] 0.9221863

For population 3 (LS-Pal) it is lower than 1, so no population structure. Yet it is a bit too low.

For population 5 (LS-All) the inflation factor is very high. This is to be expected as we have samples from structured populations and we now they do not come from a panmictic population.

                                          "P11","P12","P13","P14","P15"))

And now plot it

p1 <- ggplot(my.df %>% filter(scaffold < 14), 
             aes(x = position, y=-log10(codominant))) + 
  #geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, aes(fill=colour, col=colour)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept=0) +
  geom_point(aes(fill=colour, col=colour), size = 1) +
  facet_grid(Pop~scaffold, scales = "free_x", switch = "x") +
  geom_hline(yintercept=(-log10(0.05)),colour="white") +
  theme_classic() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("black","red")) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("black","red")) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.x = element_blank(),
        axis.line.x = element_blank(),
        strip.background = element_blank(),
        legend.position = "none") +
  labs(y = "-log10(pvalue)", x = "Chromosomes")

p1

This first graph shows the original p-values before correction. Now let's plot it after FDR correction.

p2 <- ggplot(my.df %>% filter(scaffold < 14), 
             aes(x = position, y=-log10(fdr))) + 
  #geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, aes(fill=colour, col=colour)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept=0) +
  geom_point(aes(fill=colour, col=colour), size = 1) +
  facet_grid(Pop~scaffold, scales = "free_x", switch = "x") +
  geom_hline(yintercept=(-log10(0.05)),colour="black") +
  theme_classic() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("black","red")) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("black","red")) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.x = element_blank(),
        axis.line.x = element_blank(),
        strip.background = element_blank(),
        legend.position = "none") +
  labs(y = "-log10(pvalue corrected by FDR method)", x = "Chromosomes")

p2

ggsave("../7_GWAS/7_5_PAll_pvalueVsChromosomes.png", p1,
       device = "png", dpi = 300, width = 8, height = 12)
ggsave("../7_GWAS/7_5_PAll_pvalueFDRVsChromosomes.png", p2,
